<TEXT>
an iraqi airways jetliner landed at 
gatwick airport late friday with more than 350 evacuees mostly 
american women and children who told of dwindling opposition by 
kuwaiti resistance fighters 
galina suliman a passenger from san francisco said kuwaiti 
groups were being systematically put down by the iraqis 
american andrea hanson who arrived on the uschartered boeing 
747 with her 5yearold son zach said kuwaiti resistance groups 
did not have enough weapons to fight the iraqis 
a british woman on the flight relayed one report of a group of 
16 kuwaitis being gunned down in the street by an iraqi soldier as 
they sat around chatting 
the british domestic news agency press association said there 
were believed to be 275 americans on board 43 canadians 26 
britons six japanese six australians two west germans and an 
unspecified number of indians syrians and filipinos 
however there was confusion about precise numbers press 
association initially reported 39 canadians were aboard 
an official at the us embassy in london said of the americans 
on the fight we havent got a final head count we are still 
processing 
an airport official speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
passengers included some men 
the plane left baghdad on friday afternoon and landed at gatwick 
25 miles south of london about 1130 pm 
the airport official said 30 people due to fly to gatwick had 
instead been detained in baghdad because they could not clear iraqi 
exit formalities in time she did not give their nationalities 
sky news television said the women and children on the plane are 
believed to have been among the last who expressed a wish to leave 
behind their husbands and fathers in kuwait 
the iraqis have said they are keeping men as hostages to deter 
any foreign attack on iraq 
the americans who arrived friday were booked into hotels in and 
around gatwick for the night they were due to leave for 
baltimorewashington international airport on saturday afternoon 
the 26yearold british woman who declined to gave her name for 
fear it might jeopardize her husband left behind in kuwait said 
the 16 kuwaitis had been shot on a road near kuwait city they 
were just sitting around chatting we didnt talk about it too 
much it had a very bad effect on morale 
she added the iraqis are starting to seal areas they are 
looking for weapons they are looking for foreigners 
iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 and later annexed the tiny 
oilrich neighbor 
the british woman said people living in kuwait were being 
restricted in what they could buy but iraqi soldiers were going 
into stores and taking all they wanted iraqis were also seizing 
jeeps and trucks she said 
ms hanson said that in recent days iraqi authorities had 
succeeded in partly quelling kuwaiti resistance 
resistance is very haphazard the iraqis are very successful 
at putting them down they havent got enough people they havent 
got enough weapons she said 
