<TEXT>
the snarling guard dogs that patrolled the 
berlin wall held back east germans yearning to breathe free in the 
west but they also kept an unwelcome visitor at bay the rabid 
fox 
when the wall came down dozens of the diseaseridden creatures 
began scampering into west berlin reintroducing a dreaded ailment 
that had been virtual eradicated 
since the wall crumbled last november 37 rabid foxes have been 
found in west berlin including one at a crowded swimming pool 
about 10 people have been bitten according to west berlin health 
department spokesman thomaspeter gallon 
the fall of the borders with east germany not only led to 
people moving freely but also foxes gallon said before 
rabies had been virtually wiped out 
surrounding east germany has been slow in combating rabies 
health officials said although no statistics on rabies cases in 
the east were available 
west berliners have been thrown into a minor panic by the rabies 
outbreak police have even issued warnings over radio and by 
loudspeakers from a van 
doctors have cautioned against alarm but warn bite victims to 
seek shots to stop the disease which can be fatal if untreated 
the savage guard dogs once posted along border crossings scared 
away foxes as well as people said gallon in the case of the 
foxes just the scent of the dogs was enough to keep them way 
when the wall and other border barriers came down the dogs were 
retired and the foxes found they could dash over the crumbling wall 
and into the west 
in addition to the 37 rabid foxes west berlin officials have 
found six other rabid animals since nov 9 
during the preceding 10 months there were only three rabid 
animals found in west berlin none of them foxes no one was 
bitten gallon said 
he estimated it could take up to a year to bring rabies back 
under control adding the real fear is that it could spread to dogs 
and cats 
west berlin officials have issued a public appeal for pet owners 
to be sure their beloved dogs and cats are immunized local 
veterinarians have offered special prices to help with the program 
rabies getting worse screamed the headline of the daily 
berliner morgenpost on friday now a dog is the victim of the 
disease 
the newspaper said the dog presumably bitten by a rabid fox 
had become the first pet with the disease in west berlin in five 
years another recent article said a 70yearwoman was attacked by 
a fox in a city park 
with the berlin wall opening it really went up said dr 
christian schoenfeld a leading immunologist involved in rabies 
treatment the wall was definitely a barrier 
gallon calls the rabies outbreak one of the small unavoidable 
disadvantages of the walls opening west berlin officials are 
already working with the east germans to curb the threat he said 
west germany like many western countries has had great success 
over the years by using bait laden with an immunizing substance to 
eliminate the rabies virus in the wild animal population 
schoenfeld who at one point interrupted an interview to answer 
a coworkers anxious query about rabies cautioned against 
overreaction he noted that antirabies injections are given in the 
arm now rather than the painful stomach injections administered in 
the past 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

