<TEXT>
one week before the iraqi invasion of kuwait 
the state department refused to allow the voice of america to 
broadcast an editorial critical of president saddam husseins 
threats the department cited concerns that the editorial would 
anger saddam sources say 
the case is the latest indication that some administration 
officials and congressional leaders either misread saddams 
intentions in the months preceding the invasion or believed he 
could be talked out of them 
a week before the aug 2 invasion us ambassador april glaspie 
was quoted as telling saddam that the united states understood his 
need for money to rebuild iraq after its eightyear war with iran 
we understand that and our opinion is you should have the 
opportunity to rebuild your country but we have no opinion on the 
arabarab conflicts like your border disagreement with kuwait 
ms glaspie is quoted as telling saddam 
her comments were echoed in subsequent days by officials in 
washington 
three months earlier four senate leaders met with saddam and 
assured him the united states wanted to improve relations with his 
country in response to questioning by the group led by senate 
republican leader bob dole of kansas saddam acknowledged he had 
chemical weapons and was working on a nuclear bomb 
dole assured saddam that president bush would reject attempts in 
congress to impose sanctions on iraq and might even veto them 
according to a transcript of the meeting which was taped by iraq 
without the senators knowledge 
the meeting was supposed to be private we were prevented from 
taping it but the room was bugged said doles spokesman walt 
riker who attended the april 12 meeting 
riker said the iraqi transcript was doctored to excise comments 
by saddam that agreed with us positions 
iraq also provided a transcript of the meeting with ambassador 
glaspie the state department declined to say whether it accurately 
reflected her remarks 
analysts say iraq has circulated the transcripts in an attempt 
to show that saddam did not have any indication the united states 
would object so strongly to his invasion of kuwait 
dole rejected saddams claim that the administration was leading 
a campaign against iraq on the contrary dole said a voa 
commentator who had written a critical editorial about saddam two 
months earlier was fired 
in fact the commentator was not fired riker said friday that 
dole had been misinformed by the state department 
sources say voa was sharply reprimanded for the feb 15 
editorial which said democracy requires the dismantling of secret 
police services in such countries as north korea iran libya cuba 
and iraq 
the sources also say the same editorialialist wrote the july 25 
editorial the state department refused to clear 
all voa editorials have to be cleared by the radios parent 
agency the us information agency and in the case of sensitive 
topics by the state department 
we were asked to refrain from muddying the waters as long as 
diplomatic efforts were underway in the arab world to resolve the 
crisis said a state department official of the decision to stop 
the editorial 
in the days before the invasion egypt jordan and other arab 
countries were trying through diplomacy to prevent saddam from 
fulfilling his threats 
this is all mondaymorning quarterbacking riker said of 
those who say the united states should have known better than to 
try and pacify saddam 
he said the senate group went to iraq in an attempt to find out 
saddams intentions and to warn him that he would have to improve 
his behavior if he wanted better ties with washington 
but the iraqi transcript of the meeting paints a somewhat 
different picture 
after listening to you for about an hour i realize you are a 
strong and an intelligent man and that you want peace sen 
howard metzenbaum dohio is quoted as saying 
and sen alan simpson rwyoming told saddam his problem was 
with the western media not with the us government the press 
is spoiled and conceited he is quoted as saying my advice is 
that you allow these bastards to come here and see things for 
themselves 
simpsons spokesman stan cannon said the senator was a 
wellknown advocate of press freedom and that his comments were 
taken out of context 
saddam is just trying to embarrass him cannon said 
</TEXT>
