<TEXT>
the united states is relying on un 
diplomatic backing in the persian gulf but ignoring the world 
bodys military potential 
instead us officials are trying to resurrect a middle east 
military alliance 
washington wants moscow to help blunt iraqi aggression 
ironically the earlier middle east alliance was the 1955 baghdad 
pact later called cento in which america allied with iraq against 
the soviet union 
cento unraveled in 1959 when iraq dropped out after 
revolutionaries overthrew the countrys monarchy 
in his effort to forge a new alliance president bush has urged 
soviet president mikhail gorbachev to send ships or troops to join 
the usled multinational force in the gulf 
but gorbachev has refused the soviets say they will only send 
troops as part of a un command under the direction of the 
security councils military staff committee that committee 
consists of officers from the united states soviet union britain 
france and china the five permanent council members 
the military staff committee has never been activated to 
coordinate or monitor any un military operation however even 
the korean war un command was primarily under us control with 
some allied troops pitching in 
on sept 4 secretary of state james a baker iii told congress 
the united states needs a new regional security structure in 
the middle east to deter iraqi aggression the way nato checked the 
soviets in europe 
saudi arabia bahrain oman qatar and the united arab emirates 
are the likely partners in the alliance which has yet to take 
shape 
in the process baker bypassed the united nations the world 
body already has more than 10000 military observers and 
peacekeepers in various global hot spots though the united states 
and soviet union have not contributed troops to those forces 
why has washington ignored the uns military potential 
an official at the us mission to the united nations speaking 
on condition of anonymity said thursday that activating the 
military staff committee is being explored but it will be a very 
long and slow process 
the un ambassadors of the united states soviet union 
britain france and china held two private meetings with top 
military officers from their countries flown in from washington 
for the talks 
the us mission official said the military staff committee 
could begin receiving reports on the naval enforcement of the 
unordered embargo on iraq from the united states and other 
nations involved 
this skeletal structure can now begin to grow he said 
secretary of defense dick cheney said he has no objection in 
principle to us participation in an international military 
operation however cheney said he could not imagine breaking the 
constitutional chain of command that leads up to bush as 
commanderinchief 
the pentagon of course would object vehemently to the notion 
of putting us personnel under international authority rep les 
aspin dwis said sept 7 at a gulf policy seminar 
aspin however said bush should consider the idea of a un 
command structure 
ed luck president of the un association of the usa said 
one could easily meld the idea of a regional security system with 
the un charter and with the military staff committee 
his group is a private organization that studies us policy 
toward the world body it generally advocates more active american 
involvement in the united nations 
with more un peacekeeping operations looming in the western 
sahara in africa and cambodia it is time to revive the un 
committee as a coordinating group luck added 
</TEXT>
