higher oil prices from the tensions in 
the persian gulf have opened a rift in the governing party over 
swedens plan to abolish nuclear power in 20 years 
at least half the delegates to the social democratic party 
congress which begins saturday want to postpone the nuclear 
shutdown recent polls show 
about 25 percent of swedens total energy and 50 percent of 
its electricity come from nuclear power 
the opinion over when to abolish nuclear power is divided 
within the party swedens prime minister ingvar carlsson said to 
the news agency tt last week 
in 1980 a year after the three mile island nuclear accident in 
pennsylvania swedes voted to start shutting down their nuclear 
energy plants in 1995 
oil has been viewed as the most likely alternative to nuclear 
power but the surge in price after iraqs invasion of kuwait on 
aug 2 has reminded swedes of how much their plan could cost the 
price of gasoline in sweden is already among the highest in the 
world mostly because of taxes a gallon costs about 5 
to cut the nuclear power at a fast pace we would be forced to 
use oil as an energy source in the meantime nuclear power is 
relatively inexpensive compared to the high oil prices 
acknowledged bertil karlberg a party official 
he said the social democrats want to replace nuclear energy with 
power sources such as wind and sun 
but sven bengtsson an energy expert at the ministry of 
industry said with not a lot of sunshine in sweden solar 
energy is out of the question also even if wind power is 
implemented on a large scale it can only replace a small part of 
the total energy output 
a poll published early this week by eureka research said 52 
percent of the 80 party delegates it interviewed wanted to delay 
the nuclear shutdown a party paper said thursday that nearly 50 
percent of the 350 delegates wanted to reconsider the schedule for 
closing plants which was established by parliament in 1988 
the issue promises to produce the most controversial debates of 
the sixday congress the meeting held every three years is the 
highest decisionmaking body of the social democratic party 
influential social democrats such as union leader stig malm and 
minister of energy rune molin have said the deadline for 
abolishing nuclear power should be reconsidered at the least 
molin went further there is a lot speaking in favor of 
changing everything he said 
minister of environment birgitta dahl opposes any delay in the 
shutdown and says the most important consideration is the damage a 
nuclear accident can cause 
radiation from the chernobyl nuclear accident in the soviet 
union four years ago reinforced swedish public opinion against 
nuclear power radioactive particles brought by the wind and rain 
contaminated the plants that reindeer eat forcing the lapps in 
northern sweden to slaughter hundreds of the animals they depend on 
for food 
