<TEXT>
tougher pollution controls will not only clean 
the air but help america ease its dependence on foreign oil the 
administration says in trying to head off criticism of 
antipollution bills in congress because of the oil crisis 
the environmental protection agency sought thursday to highlight 
the oilsaving potential of the clean air bill by releasing a study 
that estimated as much as 1 million barrels of oil a day could be 
saved if the legislation becomes law 
the study said the savings would come from utilities shifting 
from oil to natural gas to comply with acid rain pollution 
controls and the use of cleaner gasoline blends that contain 
nonpetroleum additives such as ethanol much of the savings would 
come toward the end of the decade 
the epa issued the report as some members of congress began 
questioning the wisdom of new and expensive pollution controls at a 
time of vaulting energy costs 
house and senate negotiators for weeks have been engaged in 
intense discussions to try to work out a final clean air bill 
before congress adjourns next month 
the conference committee members were scheduled to meet today to 
give final approval to a section of the bill requiring new 
industrial smog controls and several other provisions 
but broad sections of the legislation including those covering 
new emission controls on automobiles requirements for cleaner 
motor fuels in the most smogridden cities and curbs on acid rain 
have yet to be agreed upon 
the legislation is expected to cost industry as much as 25 
billion a year by the end of the decade when all requirements 
become effective 
opponents of the bill and industry lobbyists trying to thwart 
various sections of it have argued that such expensive controls 
are ill timed when energy prices are soaring with the potential of 
energy shortages in the months ahead 
but epa administrator william reilly said thursday the 
legislation is even more needed now 
i think the energy implications make it more urgently 
necessary than ever for congress to pass the bill said reilly in 
a telephone interview the total savings of 800000 to 1 
million barrels a day exceeds the total oil imports from kuwait and 
iraq 
according to the epa study between 300000 and 500000 barrels 
of oil a day could be saved by the end of the decade if utilities 
switch from sulfurcontaining oil to natural gas to comply with 
requirements for reducing sulfur dioxide emissions the emissions 
cause acid rain 
another 500000 barrels of oil a day could be saved because oil 
companies will have to sell cleaner fuels or gasoline blends that 
contain 15 percent or more of nonpetroleum additives the study 
said requirements for wider use of vehicles that use fuels other 
than gasoline also is expected to cut into oil demand the study 
said 
