<TEXT>
the senate has endorsed legislation through 
which the defense department would gain greater authority to block 
technology exports by us companies to iraq iran libya and syria 
for national security reasons 
senate approval of the legislation came thursday on a voice 
vote its adoption came as it was learned that the commerce 
department despite pentagon objections last february approved the 
exporting to iraq of digital imageenhancing equipment made by 
california company 
clearly that device is going to be used against our forces 
theres no denying it said stephen bryen a former deputy 
assistant defense secretary for trade policy 
the pentagon already has national security controls over exports 
to a group of primarily communist bloc countries but now can only 
advise the commerce and state departments on export licenses for 
the four arab nations targeted in the legislation 
a provision expanding the defense departments authority was 
added by sen jesse helms rnc to a bill generally loosening 
restrictions on the sale of us computers telecommunications 
equipment and machine tools to newly democratizing countries in 
eastern europe 
helms cited the commerce departments approval in february 1989 
of selling two furnaces to iraq even though the manufacturer 
acknowledged they could be used to make nuclear fuel rods for an 
atomic weapons reactor 
that sale was stopped just before iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait when the pentagon appealed to president bush after commerce 
officials had refused to allow the defense department to review the 
manufacturers export license request 
we have this situation where the defense department says 
dont do that but is overruled by the commerce department 
helms said this has occurred over and over and over again 
also as part of the bill the senate approved a measure by sen 
richard shelby dala raising civil and criminal fines for 
violating president bushs embargo against iraq from 10000 and 
50000 respectively to 250000 and 1 million 
the bill now goes to a conference with negotiators from the 
house which at the behest of us manufacturers losing out to 
japan south korea and europe on export sales voted in june to 
ease the restrictions even more 
in the united states it takes a business 114 days on average 
to get an export license complained sen john kerry dmass 
whose state is home to several high technology manufacturers 
in germany it takes just 14 days and in japan only four 
days kerry said therein lies a great deal of the story why 
the united states is struggling in the world marketplace 
the legislation reauthorizes the export administration act 
giving the president authority to restrict exports and the us 
participation in the 17nation coordinating committee for 
multilateral security controls cocom 
cocom is a cold warera multinational agency that jointly 
determines which hightech goods are too militarily sensitive to be 
sold to potential enemies in june it agreed to greatly reduce 
restrictions on sales of computers and other technology to former 
iron curtain countries in eastern europe 
meanwhile a company stuck with four multimilliondollar 
furnaces that the bush administration first approved and then 
disapproved for shipment to iraq filed a 62 million suit thursday 
against saddam husseins government 
