<TEXT>
camouflage uniforms worn by american troops 
in saudi arabia are made for cooler climates not searing desert 
heat military and clothing industry officials say 
the problem is the hot weather uniform made entirely of cotton 
doesnt have the desert camouflage pattern 
the uniform worn by troops is made of the same material half 
nylon and half cotton that was criticized as hot and 
uncomfortable by american soldiers during the 1982 invasion of 
grenada 
weather conditions are much harsher in the saudi desert than in 
grenada daytime temperatures have gone as high as 120 degrees 
since us forces were sent there in august after iraq invaded 
kuwait 
jeffrey j weinsten former chairman of an american apparel 
manufacturers association committee that oversees government 
contracts said the allcotton uniform is more comfortable than the 
blend because cotton is a moistureloving fabric that licks away 
perspiration 
the blend is not absorbent at all he said 
the allcotton uniform breathes better because it has a more 
open weave but its hard to find in the desert camouflage pattern 
weinsten said 
frank johnson a spokesman for the defense personnel support 
center in philadelphia said there are no hotweather uniforms in 
the desert pattern because the powers that be said if there is a 
war it would probably involve the warsaw pact in europe 
obviously we didnt figure on something like this breaking out 
in the middle east johnson said 
