<TEXT>
us roman catholic bishops have postponed 
action on a divisive pastoral letter about women and plan extensive 
international consultations that make its fate highly uncertain 
the decision thursday by the bishops administrative committee 
will mean a prolonged delay in final action on the letter if not 
its ultimate scuttling as some critics have demanded 
the letter in the works for five years had been scheduled for 
action in november by the fall meeting of the national conference 
of catholic bishops 
the conference president archbishop daniel e pilarczyk of 
cincinnati said the letter would only be discussed then as an 
information item and would not be considered for action 
athough not binding pastoral letters are circulated among 
catholic churches and serve as a guide for educational efforts 
preaching and the training of semarians 
the letter is called one in jesus christ a pastoral response 
to the concerns of women for church and society 
pilarczyk said the vatican had suggested consultating bishops 
outside the united states before acting on it because of the 
significance of the topic and influence of the us church 
our conference deems such a recommendation a wise one 
pilarczyk said 
last month the leadership conference of women religious 
comprised of 800 heads of womens religious orders asked that the 
proposed letter be dropped calling it intrinsically 
contradictory 
other catholic organizations and some bishops also had 
criticized the declaration as seeming to uphold equality for women 
yet hedging it and continuing to defend their exclusion from 
ordination to the priesthood 
the latest 99page draft released in march says men and women 
are equal in dignity and women should have more equitiable 
roles in leadership ministry teaching and policymaking in 
the church 
however the draft reiterated the churchs ban against ordaining 
women and defended limiting the priesthood to men as the practice 
of jesus and his apostles 
leaders of the nuns organizations said the letters position on 
equality was undermined and contradicted in its internal 
development especially in repeating the prohibition to womens 
ordination 
