<TEXT>
retail sales slumped 06 percent in august 
despite a huge jump in gasoline station purchases the government 
said today in its first report on consumer spending since the 
persian gulf crisis eruped aug 2 
some analysts had said in advance that the report would be 
skewed by sharply higher gasoline prices that would offset falling 
sales elsewhere indeed sales in nearly all other categories 
declined 
much of the increase in gasoline sales apparently represented 
increased prices rather than volume the american petroleum 
institute said gasoline prices rose about 20 percent since iraq 
overran kuwait on aug 2 
the commerce department said overall sales totaled a seasonally 
adjusted 1492 billion down from 1500 billion in july the july 
sales which rose 04 percent turned out to be stronger than the 
01 percent gain originally reported last month 
but a 11 percent advance in june had been the first increase 
since last january and analysts worried whether developments in the 
middle east would jack up prices and erode consumer confidence 
driving sales back down 
indeed two major consumer confidence surveys one conducted by 
the conference board in new york and another by the university of 
michigan plummeted after iraq invaded kuwait 
since consumer spending represents twothirds of the nations 
economic activity there was concern a dropoff could help push the 
nation into a recession retail sales account for about half of 
overall consumer spending 
the commerce report said gasoline station sales jumped 64 
percent in august the largest increase since an 83 percent 
advance in august 1979 
excluding the gasoline category retail sales tumbled even 
farther down 11 percent 
automobile sales fell 43 percent their largest drop since a 
56 percent decrease last january excluding the automobile 
category sales would have risen 04 percent 
sales of durable goods which includes cars and other items 
expected to last more than three years slid 26 percent after 
rising 07 percent the previous month 
besides automobiles other components of the durable category 
were mixed sales of building materials were off 24 percent while 
sales of furniture and other home furnishings rose 07 percent 
nondurable goods which include food and gasoline rose 06 
percent following julys 03 percent gain 
but other than gasoline all other nondurable categories fell 
sales at department stores were down 02 percent grocery 
stores off 02 percent clothing stores down 09 percent 
restaurants and bars off 07 percent and drug stores down 05 
percent 
