<TEXT>
the food and drug administration is urging 
that people cook their eggs well to prevent the spread of 
potentially fatal food contamination caused by salmonella bacteria 
cooks who use raw eggs for caesar salads bearnaise sauce 
eggnog and ice cream risk serious food poisoning the fda said 
the agency in 3500 notices sent to state and local food 
regulatory agencies recommended that intactshell eggs be 
redesignated as a potentially hazardous food because of 
increases in illnesses linked to consumption of egg products 
fda spokesman chris lecos said today the designation doesnt 
imply that a food is inherently unhealthful only that 
precautions are needed in storing and cooking it 
the notice advises that eggs be refrigerated at temperatures of 
45 degreesfahrenheit or less and thoroughly cooked at 140 degrees 
fahrenheit 
it says whole eggs should be cooked until the white is 
completely coagulated and firm and the yolk begins to thicken 
scrambled eggs need to be cooked until firm throughout 
restaurants and food service operations are told not to use raw 
eggs in uncooked readytoeat menu items and cooks are urged to 
substitute pasteurized eggs and egg products for shell eggs in 
recipes for salads sauces mayonnaise and ice cream calling for 
raw eggs 
department of agriculture figures show there were 6604 
illnesses and 43 deaths attributed to salmonella enteritidis 
bacteria between january 1985 and october last year eggs were 
implicated in 73 percent of 189 recorded outbreaks 
usda spokeswoman margaret webb said 56 salmonella outbreaks have 
been confirmed since february this year with 22 definitely linked 
to eggs she said eggs may also be implicated in other cases which 
have centered in the northeast and midatlantic states 
pennsylvania has reported nine outbreaks of the illness which 
can cause vomiting diarrhea and stomach cramps and can be fatal to 
the elderly and young children 
ms webb said the usda is trying to pinpoint infection in 
breeder flocks the chickens producing commercial hens she said 
one flock in maryland one in alabama and four in pennsylvania had 
been restricted during the current campaign 
last may the fda approved irradiation of poultry to control 
salmonella but the industry said it had no plans to use the 
procedure 
cathy mccharen vice president of the egg nutrition center in 
washington said the egg industry generally supports the 
recommendations 
if eggs were properly refrigerated there would be no 
salmonella at all she said the recommendations will force 
food handlers and restaurateurs to treat the egg with the kind of 
respect it deserves that we do want to see 
</TEXT>
