<TEXT>
retail sales dropped 06 percent in august 
the government said friday analysts said the governments first 
report on americans spending since the persian gulf crisis 
indicated growing consumer caution but not panic 
economists agreed the report was worrisome evidence of 
continuing economic weakness but said it appeared to be worse than 
it really was because of the impact of the oil shock on the service 
station sales and the way automobile sales are counted 
if you take out gas and autos it was down 01 percent said 
david berson chief economist for the federal national mortgage 
association 
the commerce department said overall sales totaled a seasonally 
adjusted 1492 billion down from 1500 billion in july and the 
largest decline since sales fell 10 percent in april 
auto sales fell 43 percent their steepest drop since sinking 
56 percent in january but economists said that reflected a 
seasonal adjustment and that actual sales were virtually unchanged 
from both june and july 
excluding automobile sales retail sales rose 04 percent in 
august 
on the other hand sales at gasoline stations jumped 64 
percent the largest increase since a 83 percent gain in august 
1979 
but analysts said the sharp hike reflected sharply higher prices 
rather than increased volume the american petroleum institute said 
gasoline prices have risen 20 percent since the iraqi invasion of 
kuwait on aug 2 
nevertheless sales would have fallen 11 percent without the 
service station category 
the simple reality is that consumers are gradually pulling 
back in their spending out of concern over a weakening job market 
and unstable conditions in the middle east said david jones an 
economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a new york government 
securities dealer 
theres no indication that will stop in the coming months 
jones added i think the economy is slowly sinking into a 
recession 
robert g dederick chief economist with the northern trust co 
in chicago contended that consumers are not showing signs of 
panicking although they are talking one thing and doing 
another 
analysts are worried about the impact of middle east 
developments on americans spending two major surveys one 
conducted by the conference board in new york and another by the 
university of michigan showed that consumer confidence plummeted 
after the iraq invasion 
because consumer spending represents twothirds of the nations 
economic activity there was concern that a dropoff could help push 
the nation into a recession retail sales account for about half of 
all consumer spending 
sales of durable goods bigticket items expected to last more 
than three years slid 26 percent after rising 07 percent in the 
preceding month 
besides automobiles the building material component also fell 
down 24 percent sales of furniture and other home furnishings 
rose 07 percent 
nondurable goods sales rose 06 percent following julys 03 
percent gain 
except for gasoline all nondurable categories fell 
sales at department stores were down 02 percent grocery 
stores off 02 percent clothing stores down 09 percent 
restaurants and bars off 07 percent and drug stores down 05 
percent 
