<TEXT>
samuel s stratton a new york democrat who 
served in the house for 30 years has died of a heart attack he 
was 73 
stratton died thursday after being stricken at the potomac 
nursing home where he had lived since last year he announced in 
july 1988 that he was too ill to seek reelection 
new york gov mario cuomo praised stratton for his dedication 
and tireless leadership saying he displayed wisdom and the 
unstinting willingness to serve 
other colleagues remembered him friday as a champion of a strong 
national defense and an unflagging public servant 
sam was the epitome of what a congressman should be said 
republican rep frank horton who succeeded stratton as dean of the 
new york congressional delegation he was quick to respond to the 
needs of his constituents and his knwledge and integrity earned 
him the respect of both republicans and democrats alike 
a democrat whose hawkish views broke with party tradition 
stratton favored most proposed increases in defense spending and 
new weapons systems including the b1 bomber mx missile and 
neutron bomb 
but he considered himself a middleoftheroad democrat and had 
voted against an antibusing amendment to the constitution and 
supported such liberal causes as a national minimum welfare 
payment and economic sanctions against south africa 
strattons biggest congressional defeat was in never becoming 
chairman of the armed services committee he was passed over for 
the younger and lesssenior rep les aspin dwis 
stratton was born in 1916 in yonkers ny he graduated from the 
university of rochester and earned masters degrees from haverford 
college and harvard university 
he served during world war ii as a naval combat intelligence 
officer on the staff of gen douglas macarthur he twice was 
awarded the bronze star 
stratton was first elected to the house in 1958 the only 
democrat in 42 years to be sent to congress from what was then the 
32nd congressional district 
stratton is survived by his wife joan and five children 
</TEXT>
