<TEXT>
ben smathers whose agile legs and fast 
feet helped spread the popularity of clog dancing during a 32year 
career on the grand ole opry has died he was 61 
the leader of the stoney mountain cloggers died thursday of 
complications following openheart surgery he had been admitted to 
vanderbilt hospital on tuesday complaining of an upset stomach and 
heartburn 
smathers an asheville nc native learned the dance as a 
child by watching an old man do it in the mountains of western 
north carolina a hallmark of appalachian culture clogging is 
basically keeping the beat of the music by tapping the feet 
in a 1986 interview he said the key to doing the dance well was 
the emotional grasp of its spirit 
if you cant feel it in your heart it has no meaning he 
told the associated press 
his eightmember stoney mountain cloggers often danced on the 
opry to fiddle tunes such as black mountain rag and old joe 
clark 
the group had made frequent appearances with the charlie daniels 
band dancing to the highpowered fiddle classic orange blossom 
special as a climax to each show 
in the late 1960s and early 1970s smathers and his group 
performed with roy rogers and dale evans at fairs rodeos and other 
appearances 
he made six lowbudget movies and performed the native folk 
dance twice in new yorks carnegie hall he also appeared 300 times 
on network tv shows 
he suffered a heart attack in 1979 and doctors told him then he 
would never dance again he proved them wrong by returning to the 
stage in six months 
they dont call you home til your works done he said 
about his recovery 
funeral arrangements were incomplete survivors include his 
mother wife three sons and three daughters 
</TEXT>
