<DOCNO> AP900914-0133 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a senate panel friday endorsed a pair of 
ussoviet treaties more than a decade after the pacts aimed at 
curbing nuclear weapons testing were drafted 
the senate foreign relations committee took the action on an 
180 vote sending the two treaties to the full senate for 
ratification 
the threshold test ban treaty of 1974 places a limit of 150 
kilotons on the size of weapons tests and provides detailed 
standards for the tests to ensure each side can accurately measure 
the others explosions 
the peaceful nuclear explosions treaty of 1976 drawn up 
primarily to seal off possible loopholes in the ttb treaty puts 
identical limits on nuclear blasts for peaceful purposes such as 
excavation or seismic exploration 
both treaties which languished for years because of misgivings 
over us ability to verify soviet compliance lag far behind 
current armscontrol reality which contemplates massive reductions 
in each sides nuclear arsenals 
new verification protocols agreed to june 1 by president bush 
and soviet president mikhail gorbachev during their washington 
summit have largely cleared away the misgivings 
in fact the protocols have in some ways become more important 
than the treaties because they set up a new process of intrusive 
onsite inspections by both sides procedures that may become a 
model for a sweeping strategic arms agreement 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

