the senate cleared the way friday for action 
on a bill that would require automakers to dramatically increase 
fuel economy 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said he hoped 
to have a vote late next week on the bill that would require 
automakers to increase average fuel economy of new cars to 35 miles 
per gallon by 1995 and to 40 miles per gallon by 2001 
supporters contend the higher fuel economy requirements would 
save 28 million barrels of oil a day once they go fully into 
effect but key opponents promised to continue fighting the measure 
on the senate floor 
within hours of the vote transportation secretary samuel 
skinner blasted the legislation as unrealistic irresponsible 
and more important unattainable he said theres no technology 
to achieve the bills goals without making cars smaller 
it should be called the highway fatality bill skinner said 
at a news conference citing a new study by the national highway 
traffic safety administration that concluded a clear link between 
reducing the size of cars and traffic deaths 
the nhtsa study said the introduction of smaller cars over the 
past decade had resulted in an estimated 1340 additional traffic 
deaths annually in singlecar accidents based on those numbers 
nhtsa administrator jerry curry said between 600 and 1140 
additional deaths annually can be expected if automakers try to 
meet the 40 mile per gallon standard 
