<TEXT>
delegates from about 100 countries pledged to seek 
tighter conditions for exports of nuclear materials to countries 
that have not signed a treaty banning the spread of atomic weapons 
diplomats said friday 
oswaldo de rivero chairman of a conference reviewing compliance 
with the 1970 nonproliferation treaty said such a wide 
international call for tougher controls was unprecedented 
in a separate measure prompted partly by iraqs invasion of 
kuwait delegates urged the international atomic energy agency to 
strenthen its surveillance of nuclear installations to prevent 
clandestine production of atomic weapons 
iraq signed the nonproliferation treaty but has tried to import 
components that could be used in the manufacture of nuclear bombs 
the two recommendations were part of a final conference 
declaration that was expected to be adopted over the weekend 
delegates agreed to ask the viennabased international atomic 
energy agency to consider starting shortnotice inspections it 
currently inspects according to a fixed schedule 
participants also agreed to recommend to exporters of nuclear 
materials that they require as a precondition of doing 
business that customers have all atomic installations under the 
agencys surveillance de rivero told reporters 
the move is aimed at countries that have not signed the 
nonproliferation treaty and are believed to have nuclear weapons 
capability they include israel south africa brazil argentina 
india and pakistan 
the united states canada australia and sweden have already 
banned nuclear exports to countries refusing full inspection west 
german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher told the conference 
his country plans to adopt the same restriction 
in a mainly symbolic move the united states the soviet union 
and britain pledged for the first time to defend nonnuclear states 
from attack de rivero said they are the three nations with 
nuclear capability that also have signed the nonproliferation 
treaty 
the move appeared aimed at addressing longtime concerns among 
nonnuclear states that the treaty is fundamentally unbalanced 
the treaty requires states that do not possess nuclear weapons 
to refrain from building or acquiring them in return the united 
states soviet union and britain pledge to work toward eliminating 
their arsenals and provide peaceful nuclear technology to other 
nations 
members meet every five years to review the treatys success 
about twothirds of the 141 member countries are attending the 
current session 
debate over disarmament goals was subdued this year because of 
superpower efforts to cut nuclear arms since 1985 and the lessening 
of cold war tensions de rivero said 
this produced a lot of compromises and tolerance among the 
parties he said 
two nuclear weapon states france and china are not formally 
affected by the conference since both have not signed the treaty 
however both sent conference observers for the first time in 
what western diplomats said was a sign that they might sign on 
in an annex to the final declaration france and china will join 
the three other nuclear states in reaffirming previous guarantees 
that they will never attack a nonnuclear state de rivero said 
