<TEXT>
warning the federal government says homemade 
eggnog can be hazardous to your health 
so can homemade mayonnaise caesar salad and other dishes 
containing raw eggs 
the food and drug administration recommended friday that raw 
eggs be classified as a potentially hazardous food and said 
that improperly cooked eggs raise the danger of salmonella food 
poisoning 
specifically the agency urged people to stop using raw eggs for 
such dishes as caesar salad homemade mayonnaise eggnog and ice 
cream 
the warning was contained in 3500 notices sent to state and 
local food regulatory agencies 
labeling a food as potentially hazardous doesnt mean that 
a food is inherently unhealthful fda spokesman chris lecos said 
he said other perishable but perfectly wholesome nutritious 
foods such as meats dairy products and cooked vegetables are also 
considered potentially hazardous 
but he said the fda in conjunction with the agriculture 
department is trying to halt the spread of the salmonella 
enteriditis bacteria which has entered the genetic systems of some 
layer hens and contaminated their eggs 
agriculture department figures show there were 6604 illnesses 
and 43 deaths attributed to salmonella from january 1985 to last 
october eggs were implicated in 73 percent of 189 recorded 
outbreaks 
the fda notice advises that eggs be refrigerated at temperatures 
of 45 degrees fahrenheit or less and thoroughly cooked at 140 
degrees fahrenheit 
it says whole eggs should be cooked until the white is 
completely coagulated and firm and the yolk begins to thicken 
scrambled eggs need to be cooked until firm throughout 
restaurants and food service operations are told not to use raw 
eggs in uncooked readytoeat menu items and cooks are urged to 
substitute pasteurized eggs and egg products for shell eggs in 
recipes for salads sauces mayonnaise and ice cream calling for 
raw eggs 
louis b raffel president of the american egg board said egg 
producers agree on the need for precautions the industrys 
feeling is that eggs should be refrigerated and that proper 
handling at all levels is important to avoid any foodrelated 
diseases 
cathy mccharen vice president of the egg nutrition center in 
washington said the industry has been giving similar advice for 
the last two years the recommendations will force food handlers 
and restaurateurs to treat the egg with the kind of respect it 
deserves that we do want to see 
usda spokeswoman margaret webb said 56 salmonella outbreaks have 
been confirmed since february with 22 definitely linked to eggs 
she said eggs may also be implicated in other cases which have 
centered in the northeast and midatlantic states 
pennsylvania has reported nine outbreaks of the illness which 
can cause vomiting diarrhea and stomach cramps and can be fatal to 
the elderly and young children 
</TEXT>
