<TEXT>
californias first planned toll roads 
were announced friday marking the first time that freewayhappy 
motorists will face levies on anything but bridges 
the roads all privately financed under a new stateapproved 
program include a 12 billion 40mile highway east of san 
francisco and a 10mile segment in san diego county near the 
mexican border two other projects were approved for orange county 
just south of los angeles 
all are set for completion by 1997 
gov george deukmejian also said two backup plans were approved 
in case financing or other problems blocked the toll roads one 
would replace san franciscos earthquakedamaged embarcadero 
freeway with an underground highway and the other would construct 
a highspeed train from the los angeles international airport to 
palmdale in the mohave desert 
while privitizing roads is not new in the country 
californias approach is unique because the private sector 
selects the projects from among those already on a list of planned 
future state highways deukmejian said 
the toll roads would all be constructed with private funds with 
the state and developers negotiating the tolls before construction 
begins bob best the director of the state department of 
transportation told a news conference that he expected tolls to 
run between 10 and 20 cents per mile 
the toll roads program was part of the political compromise that 
led to the 9centspergallon gasoline tax increase approved by 
california voters in june 
the planned toll roads would be 
in orange county an 11mile road roughly between anaheim 
stadium and the john wayne airport and 10 miles of new toll lanes 
on the route 91 freeway to riverside county 
in san diego county a new fourlane freeway extending 10 miles 
from the otay mesa road near the mexican border north to state 
route 54 at an estimated cost of 400 million 
in contra costa county east of san francisco a five or 
sixlane 40mile road between antioch and interstate 680 near 
sunol 
