<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators gave formal 
approval friday to a compromise provision of the clean air bill 
that would require factories and businesses to tighen controls on 
smogcausing pollutants 
the provisions had tentatively been approved in negotiations 
among staff members earlier in the week and had expected to be 
endorsed by the house and senate members 
the industrial smog measure is part of a much broader clean air 
bill that would impose tough new pollution controls on electric 
utilities automobiles and factories including reductions in 
sulfer dioxide and the industrial release of toxic chemicals 
the agreement would require even small emitters of smogcausing 
pollution like dry cleaners bakeries and furniture makers to 
comply with tougher controls by installing new pollution control 
equipment 
the senate had exempted polluters releasing less than 100 tons 
of pollution a year but the house version which was adopted by 
the conferees requires compliance by polluters of as little as 25 
to 50 tons a year in cities with serious smog problems 
after the industrial smog section was approved conferees agreed 
to proceed to a section of the massive bill that deals with new 
pollution controls on motor vehicles 
both the house and senate approved clean air bills earlier this 
year but the negotiations are aimed at resolving an array of 
differences including how much to toughen the pollution controls on 
cars buses and trucks 
the legislation would be the first strengthening of federal air 
pollution controls in 13 years 
</TEXT>
