<TEXT>
art lovers with a fertile imagination will have 
a rich field to till as they stroll through sculptor joel shapiros 
exhibit at the baltimore museum of art 
most of the 25 works are made of simple blocks of wood or 
bronze and suggest human or other figures in a wide array of 
activity and emotion 
his ability to create these impressions is what makes the 
exhibit joel shapiro tracing the figure a success said 
brenda richardson the museums curator of painting and sculpture 
joel is more accessible its easier for us to get close to 
his work said richardson who collaborated with the artist in 
designing the exhibit 
the exhibit opened in august and runs through oct 7 at the 
baltimore museum of art after which it will travel to the des 
moines art center and the center for fine arts in miami 
very often when people see a minimalist exhibit they feel 
hostile shut out many people feel very remote from it 
richardson said that is not the response people have to 
shapiro 
shapiro 48 is a new york native who calls himself a 
postminimalist like the minimalists before him he uses the most 
basic of shapes but unlike them he goes beyond pure abstraction 
and provides something more concrete to think about 
i want the work to be loaded with emotion loaded with 
reference but not to the point where its gratuitous he said 
from his summer home and studio in westport ny 
therefore shapiros sculptures have no faces only the simplest 
representations of body parts and no titles still they succeed 
in conveying emotion a tiny man kneeling in supplication joyful 
kicking dancers with flailing arms a walking figure staring at the 
ground apparently lost in thought 
some stimulate the imagination enough to bring several different 
ideas to mind 
at first glance a series of painted wood blocks clearly suggest 
a figure resting on its side with its left foot bent in another 
moment or from another angle the figure disappears and the blocks 
look more like a model of an apartment building 
from one angle a 7foothigh bronze piece might suggest a giant 
bird taking off from another it could be a strutting drum major 
he doesnt put into it either a bird or drum major thats 
precisely what he wants you to do richardson said even as you 
may grasp a figure you may lose that figure especially as you 
walk around it 
shapiro says the images people glean from his sculptures are 
often different from his own ideas in creating them 
he accepts that as the price for displaying art in public 
im open i think im comfortable with peoples response to 
the work as long as they react to it and dont walk away 
shapiros roots offer little on the origins of his art his 
father was a doctor his mother a biochemist 
after college he spent two years in the peace corps in the late 
1960s his experience in another culture helped him get a better 
perspective on his own interests i became an artist because 
thats what i did best i chose sculpture because it was very much 
in the real world and not hanging on a wall 
shapiros work wasnt always as tangible is the work displayed 
in the exhibit before the mid70s he created more inanimate 
objects such as a tiny chair tiny homes coffins or ladders they 
implied the presence of the human form through its absence 
there was a point where i avoided using the figure he said 
then there was a point where i just abandoned that limitation i 
felt that by using figuration i could allow more into the 
work also it had to do with wanting the work to be more so you 
would have an almost oneonone experience with it 
