<TEXT>
one of russias great abstract painters of the 
20th century out of favor when socialist realism was the only 
art for the soviets gets his biggest exhibit here on sunday 55 
years after his death 
kazimir severinovich malevich pronounced malyayvitch never 
went to prison as far as anyone can ascertain today however the 
director of the kiev art gallery was given a long sentence for 
mounting a show of his work 
malevich himself was arrested in 1930 after a trip to the west 
and questioned about ideologies deviations and right and left 
tendencies his friends burned some of his voluminous writings 
just in case 
he was one of the greatest and most original spokesman of the 
entire russian avantgarde soviet leader mikhail gorbachev wrote 
in the current catalog for the exhibit kazimir malevich 
18781935 raisa gorbachev added a tribute of her own 
and president bush in a letter welcoming the exhibit wrote 
the creative forms of kazimir malevich may be as complex and 
varied as the range of human emotions yet they unite us in our 
appreciation for his talent and vision 
work of these avantgarde artists for decades was confined to 
the cellars of soviet museums under gorbachevs policies of 
openness and reconstruction the soviets brought out malevichs 
work for a show in 1988 
armand hammer the american industrialist who has known soviet 
leaders since lenin helped get the pictures for the national 
gallery of art 
the russians rarely say nyet to hammer explained j 
carter brown director the national gallery 
after the exhibition closes at the national gallery on nov 4 
it will go to los angeles as the inaugural show at the armand 
hammer museum and cultural center 
malevich the son of a sugar mill manager produced his first 
finished painting in 1889 when he was 11 in the early years of 
the century he learned in moscow about the works of the great 
french impressionists and postimpressionists of the period he 
painted in versions of west european styles but always with a 
distinctive russian flavor 
some of his works resemble the paintings of fernand leger piet 
mondrian and even the distinctive stylings of paul cezanne 
malevich gradually moved away from pictures of recognizable people 
and objects 
world war i was a time of radical art movements in russia each 
with a fanciful name though he was asked not to antagonize the 
public by introducing still another name malevich called his own 
theory suprematism 
a key painting which has led to most comment over the years 
was simply a black square analysts claim to see many things under 
the unrelieved blackness visitors who prefer less abstract art may 
get more from his earlier and later work 
today we have advanced into a new fourth dimension of 
motion malevich wrote we have pulled up our consciousness by 
its roots from the earth it is now free to revolve in the infinity 
of space 
angelica zander rudenstine curator of the exhibit says that by 
suprematism he meant a higher kind of painting than the 
representation of familiar objects 
malevich joined enthusiastically in the revolutionary movements 
of 1917 in the first days of the soviet government it appointed 
him commissar for the preservation of monuments and antiquities 
especially those in the kremlin but when he visited the west in 
1929 with paintings for a show in berlin he took the precaution of 
leaving them behind 
many were acquired later by the stadelijk museum in amsterdam 
and brought to washington for the current show 
toward the end of his life malevich returned to painting 
recognizable figures but they were flat and unrealistic not 
socialist realism at all some he did in a much earlier style and 
put earlier dates on them his last works were realistic portraits 
including a selfportrait in which he wore clothes of the italian 
renaissance 
the exhibit will be at the armand hammer museum and cultural 
