<TEXT>
one year after hurricane hugo smashed 
ashore charleston still bears the scars from the most destructive 
hurricane ever to hit the us mainland 
shingles are missing from the tattered roof of st michaels 
episcopal church the oldest in the city and the spire at the top 
of the bell tower has yet to be replaced 
the nearby charleston county courthouse stands empty its roof 
destroyed masking tape still lines its windows preparation for 
the storm that thundered ashore a year ago this week 
but across meeting street city hall bustles with the business 
of government just as it did that lightless night last sept 21 
when hugo crashed into south carolina packing winds of 135 mph 
hugos wrath claimed 29 lives on the us mainland and was felt 
across hundreds of miles from fishing communities on the south 
carolina coast to mill towns nestled in the north carolina 
mountains the storm caused an estimated 59 billion damage 
a year later the recovery both physical and emotional 
continues but for a relatively small poor state a lot has been 
done in the past 12 months to put things back in order 
its a miracle were back where we are given the enormity of 
the storm that hit us and the fact that over half our state was 
declared a disaster area gov carroll campbell said 
he noted that the beaches have been repaired and the tourism 
industry has rebounded 
the historic district the heart of charlestons tourist 
economy was scrubbed up in quick order indeed visitors would 
have trouble telling charleston took the brunt of such a severe 
storm 
the recovery has been phenomenal said mayor joseph p riley 
jr it is almost a miracle its a tribute to the citizens of the 
community they didnt cry or whine or get angry everybody got to 
work and pitched in 
during the past year the city opened a waterfront park and a 
new visitors center is nearing completion 
the city has not only recovered this was not a year we 
treaded water riley said 
but the recovery among the rural poor has taken longer the 
sound of hammers and the buzz of power saws still can be heard on 
the hardhit barrier islands northeast of town 
following hugo hundreds of tons of supplies and about 37 
million in donations flooded into charleston last month the final 
1 million was distributed to relief agencies 
richard hendry of the trident community foundation said more 
could have been used there was not near enough to meet requests 
which totaled almost 8 million he said 
the needs are still being uncovered hendry said 
in rural berkeley county about 150 people wait to have homes 
repaired or rebuilt said henry bonner executive director of 
berkeley county interfaith disaster ministries 
no matter how much publicity weve had since the storm its 
surprising how many people hear about us by wordofmouth for the 
first time bonner said 
the donations of money and building supplies that followed the 
storm have tapered off now most of the help comes from south 
carolinians 
were finding since the emergency a lot of people have been 
able to get friends and relatives to help in the repairs bonner 
added last winter people were struggling to get over the storm 
they couldnt help each other 
hugo brought a building boom to the sea islands 
vacant lots remain in places where weathered bungalows once 
lined the beach much of the debris has been cleared and new 
houses are going up 
but a block from the ocean on sullivans island weeds sprout 
through the floorboards of a rusted red sports car the car sits in 
front of a shattered house next to the battered hulk of a pickup 
truck 
next door a crew of about 20 workers labors in the hot sun on a 
new beach house with an ocean view 
to the north in the small shrimping hamlet of mcclellanville 
streets have been cleared of debris the local shrimp fleet is 
again plying the atlantic but the rotting hulls of two shrimp 
boats tossed ashore by hugo still bear mute witness to the storms 
fury 
it was a boom year for construction with thousands of workers 
flooding the area officials estimate about 3 billion was pumped 
into the charleston area economy for construction services and 
trade 
many of the physical scars have healed but the emotional toll 
is more difficult to assess 
the hugo outreach program sponsored by the state department of 
mental health counseled more than 26000 people during the past 
year 
during recent weeks an increase has been noted in requests for 
help said cathy joyner a counselor with the program 
were seeing a lot of people who have not physically 
recovered and they realize they are frightened and anxious she 
said an anniversary is an opportunity to go back and reevaluate 
where they were a year ago and see if they have made any progress 
it will be frightening for a lot of people to see they are not 
where they want to be 
since hugo there have been increases in domestic abuse reports 
people seeking help with drinking problems and divorce filings 
counselors say 20000 south carolinians could suffer longterm 
psychological problems officials hope the outreach program which 
includes 50 counselors statewide can be extended through spring 
local governments will mark the storm anniversary with a 
candlelight observance at city hall several commercial events also 
will note the occasion including a road race and a golf 
exposition 
for some it will be a trying time 
lynn ziegler heads the building committee for the sunrise 
presbyterian church on sullivans island 
the church was destroyed in the storm and the congregation has 
met in a tent since last january a new building wont be in place 
until next year 
mrs zieglers house on the isle of palms was not severely 
damaged and she said she suffered from survivors guilt 
i had been praying for some way to help said mrs ziegler 
who worked in relief efforts after the storm when asked to chair 
the building committee i felt i was unqualified 
but then i saw this was the answer to my prayers she said 
