asahi breweries ltd said friday it has proposed to 
buy a nearly 20 percent equity stake in elders ixl ltd 
australias largest brewer for 110 billion yen or about 809 
million 
the investment would be made late in october under a basic 
agreement with harlin holding pty ltd of australia elders 
biggest shareholder asahi officials said 
if the deal is completed asahi would be the second biggest 
shareholder in elders after harlin which currently has a 56 
percent stake the asahi officials said 
peter bartels chief executive of elders ixl said in a 
statement from melbourne we would welcome the opportunity 
presented by this transaction for both organizations to enlarge 
their presence internationally 
he said elders planned to discuss the proposal from harlin with 
its its advisers and that it board would meet to consider the 
matter 
the elders group comprising three affiliated breweries has a 
35 percent share of the worlds beer market 
its whollyowned carlton and united breweries subsidiary has a 
48 percent share in the australian beer market its main brand is 
fosters 
elders has about 10 percent of the british beer market through 
its courage ltd unit and its jointlyowned molson breweries in 
canada holds 52 percent of the canadian beer market according to 
industry estimates 
asahi has a 25 percent share in japans beer market up from 10 
percent four years ago before its 1987 introduction of dry beer 
dry beer is considered less sweet than regular beer and it has 
proven very popular in japan prompting other brewers to produce 
their versions of dry beer 
