<TEXT>
taiwan will open its stock market to 
foreign institutional investors in a bid to curb speculation by 
local investors the securities and exchange commission announced 
friday 
chang changpang commission chairman said his agency wants to 
allow foreign banks insurance companies and fund management 
agencies to invest in taiwans stocks beneficiary certificates 
government and corporate bonds 
we believe the participation of foreign institutional 
investors would help curb speculation and stabilize the market 
he said 
under the proposal total foreign investment in the market would 
be limited to 25 billion of the total 130 billion invested in 
the market chang said he said all transactions should be made 
through designated agents or representatives in taiwan 
each foreign institutional investor who can invest between 5 
million and 50 million in taiwan stocks can purchase up to 5 
percent of the shares in a listed taiwan stock he said 
however combined foreign investment should not exceed 10 
percent of any individual stock he added 
the commissions proposal will be submitted to the cabinet for 
final approval he said 
the taiwan stock exchanges weighted index jumped more than 150 
percent from the opening session in 1989 to 1249534 on feb 10 
this year before plunging to as low as 313556 on aug 24 
