<TEXT>
the resolution trust corp has been selling an 
estimated 50 million to 75 million worth of junk bonds weekly 
chipping away at its 29 billion portfolio from failed savings and 
loans 
for the most part the weak junk market has been able to absorb 
the selling without plunging further than it has already on fears 
of a sluggish economy 
there are still buyers in todays market willing to invest in 
what they see has value said joseph bencivenga head of 
highyield or junk bond research at salomon brothers inc 
a number of reasons are offered for the bond markets resilience 
to the rtc sales but many point to the decision by the thrift 
bailout agency to unload the securities slowly 
the rtc has done a good job of metering the flow in the 
beginning people were afraid they would dump hundreds of millions a 
day bencivenga said 
during a slightly busier than normal week the rtc sold about 
70 million worth of bonds tuesday and offered 40 million more 
wednesday market observers said the rtc has been able to avoid a 
great shock to a market that handles 100 million to 200 million 
worth of bonds daily 
when the government announced it would sell assets from failed 
thrifts including highyield bonds many feared the bond sales 
would further depress the market 
junk prices have slumped for most of the past year since 
investors became skittish after the highly leveraged retail empire 
of campeau corp began to come apart 
junk bonds pay higher interest than investmentgrade bonds to 
compensate for the increased risk that the company issuing the 
bonds wont be able to make payments on them 
i think the sales have hurt the market but everyone has long 
since discounted the sales tempering the damage said paul 
getman an economist at regional financial associates inc in west 
chester pa when it first got wind that the rtc was going to be 
seizing thrifts with large junk portfolios the market really fell 
apart 
despite the depressed market the rtc cannot wait for better 
days the agency is in business to get rid of the bonds and other 
assets from failed thrifts and apparently wants to do it before the 
market gets worse 
the value of many of the rtcs bonds is depressed but if the 
economy continues to slow and consumers spend less the companies 
that issued the bonds may have less money to pay interest and 
principal that would push the market value of the bonds down even 
further 
thrift regulators last week blocked columbia savings amp loan from 
selling 3 billion of its junk bonds to a group of investors 
primarily from canada and hong kong regulators apparently feared 
the deal could leave the government holding the bonds if their 
market value declines further 
under the deal the investor group called gordon america lp 
would pay 300 million up front and give columbia a 10year note 
paying 105 percent interest for the remaining 27 billion 
gordon america had an escape route that apparently left 
regulators concerned the government would wind up getting the bonds 
at a price even lower than they are now 
if the value of the bonds fell 10 percent below the purchase 
price the buyers could have walked away from the deal losing 
their down payment but avoiding further losses the bonds would 
then go back to beverly hills califbased columbia and if it 
were seized by regulators to the government 
regulators say they would support an allcash deal in which 
columbia gets rid of the bonds for good 
