<TEXT>
keith adams was helping his father unload 
corn on their iowa farm one day but he climbed into the wagon and 
was sucked into the grain as if it were quicksand he suffocated 
keith was 11 
his mother marilyn adams of earlham iowa soon discovered her 
sons tragedy was no freak accident many others had been pulled 
into flowing grain in wagons and bins and suffocated 
mrs adams decided to design decals warning flowing grain 
traps and suffocates victims in seconds and never play in or 
on this wagon 
she also broadened the scope of her crusade and formed farm 
safety for just kids the group produces literature and video tapes 
on farm safety and arranges workshops and school presentations 
farming is one of the nations most dangerous occupations and 
the families of victims of farm tragedies are using their stories 
to warn others and to improve agricultures safety record 
farmers are beginning to change their behavior and attitude 
said mrs adams mom has a reason now to tell dad that johnny is 
not going with him to do something today keeping kids alive is a 
top priority 
farming the nations deadliest job in 1988 improved to second 
place behind mining in 1989 with 42 deaths per 100000 workers 
but the death rate for all industry is nine per 100000 and the 
agriculture statistics do not include 200 to 300 deaths of 
youngsters said larry williams a farm safety expert with country 
companies insurance group 
in addition to 1300 farm deaths 130000 disabling injuries 
occurred last year country companies estimates the loss at 36 
billion 
ralph wier 63 was hurrying to finish his farm chores so he 
could go to the bank but his tractor overturned and crushed him to 
death 
delight wier lost her husband in 1987 her 3yearold son caught 
his leg in a wagon auger in 1958 and died her 12yearold daughter 
fell on an electric fence in 1970 and died 
mrs wier who lives near lacon now writes magazine columns and 
books and stresses safety to other farm families she and son jon 
also practice what they preach on their 1000acre marshall county 
farm 
we have seat belts and rollbars on our tractors and 
slowmoving vehicle signs on all machinery that goes on the 
highway said mrs wier who has taken implement safety courses 
and learned cpr 
accidents happen when farmers are under stress so i insist 
they take breaks she said i dont think itsa favor to take 
food to them in the field they should stop and come in the house 
and rest 
the best rule for farm children is to avoid the dangers from 
mowers to slurry pits 
various reasons for the dangers exist experts cite the vast 
array of heavy machinery and large animals the fatigue associated 
with long hours of work during planting and harvest seasons the 
constant exposure of living at the workplace and the long distance 
to hospitals 
children seem to be attracted to farm equipment because of its 
size and power said williams adding that they also want to help 
their parents 
children are most often injured while riding on machinery with 
an adult farmers are most often killed when their tractors roll 
over and pin them 
solutions can be as simple and inexpensive as not allowing extra 
riders on implements or as costly as the 400 to 1500 to add 
seat belts and rollbars to an older tractor said bob aherin a 
university of illinois farm safety specialist 
he said farmers also are encouraged to attend safety workshops 
now offered in rural communities to read and follow instructions 
in equipment manuals to wear protective clothing and to know 
their limitations 
aherin said a bill in congress would provide 320 million over 
five years to improve farm safety 
the measure would pay for research on health and safety issues 
rehabilitation programs for injured farmers training for rescue 
workers education on farm safety and a national data collection 
system on accidents 
</TEXT>
