<TEXT>
it wasnt the biggest headline of the week but 
the new york stock exchanges approval of extended trading hours 
provided an entry for the history books 
the board of the worlds bestknown stock market put its stamp 
on the first stages of a plan that could lead to roundtheclock 
trading within five to 10 years 
approved were two afterhours trading sessions that will allow 
big market players to execute trades after the nyses closing bell 
at 4 pm eastern time 
up to now such business has been flowing overseas hence the 
motivation for the exchanges unprecedented move 
it was a small step the sessions will only last about an hour 
and are aimed at big stock traders not individuals but the late 
sessions are nevertheless a giant leap for the traditionbound big 
board 
the sessions wont require the services of the socalled 
specialists who manage trading on the floor of the exchange 
during regular business hours the postclose sessions propose to 
match buyers and sellers electronically as they are in london 
the new crossing sessions wont radically alter wall street 
life as the world knows it individual stocks will trade at their 
closing prices 
but later stages of the plan call for stock auctions several 
times a night and then 24hour trading before the year 2000 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
six weeks into the persian gulf crisis rumors were supplanting 
headlines as the currency of the financial markets oil futures 
trading in particular caromed from rumor to rumor 
the impact was most apparent monday when lower oil prices were 
suddenly pushed higher on reports of iraqi troop movement toward 
jordan 
officials at the new york mercantile exchange seeming more 
suspicious than usual about the circulation of false reports said 
they would investigate to determine whether any gossip was being 
spread to influence prices 
meanwhile oil appeared to be establishing a base at 30 per 
barrel evidence to some experts that the rumor mill was helping 
support that floor 
stocks for their part started to pay more attention to the 
economy a 43point drop in the dow jones industrial average 
thursday was blamed on fears of rising inflation 
</TEXT>
