<TEXT>
the senate cleared the way friday for action 
on a bill that would require automakers to dramatically increase 
fuel economy 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said he hoped 
to have a vote late next week on the bill that would require 
automakers to increase average fuel economy of new cars to 35 miles 
per gallon by 1995 and to 40 miles per gallon by 2001 
supporters contend the higher fuel economy requirements would 
save 28 million barrels of oil a day once they go fully into 
effect but key opponents promised to continue fighting the measure 
on the senate floor 
within hours of the vote transportation secretary samuel 
skinner blasted the legislation as unrealistic irresponsible 
and more important unattainable he said theres no technology 
to achieve the bills goals without making cars smaller 
it should be called the highway fatality bill skinner said 
at a news conference citing a new study by the national highway 
traffic safety administration that concluded a clear link between 
reducing the size of cars and traffic deaths 
the nhtsa study said the introduction of smaller cars over the 
past decade had resulted in an estimated 1340 additional traffic 
deaths annually in singlecar accidents based on those numbers 
nhtsa administrator jerry curry said between 600 and 1140 
additional deaths annually can be expected if automakers try to 
meet the 40 mile per gallon standard 
skinner said automakers had convinced him that the senate bills 
fuel economy goals cant be achieved without substantial weight 
reductions in cars 
weve just had the first inning of this nineinning game 
sen donald riegle dmich said after the senate voted 6828 to 
clear the way for debate 
we hope and intend to win this fight riegle said adding 
that he doubts supporters will get the needed 60 votes to cut off 
debate and bring it to a vote next week 
a similar bill has been introduced in the house but it has yet 
to be taken up by the energy and commerce committee whose 
chairman rep john dingell dmich is staunchly opposed to the 
measure 
rep barbara boxer dcalif sponsor of the house bill said 
earlier this week she would try to push the legislation directly on 
the house floor in an effort to bypass dingells committee 
but the senates 6828 vote friday to cut off efforts by riegle 
to keep the measure off the senate floor was an indication of the 
growing support in congress for a measure to reduce us reliance 
on foreign oil a subject in the spotlight since iraqs invasion of 
kuwait 
its the single most important step to reducing our dependency 
on opec oil and curbing global warming the sierra club said of 
the bill sponsored by sen richard bryan dnev 
in floor debate riegle said those fuel savings arent likely to 
begin phasing in until 1995 and a better response to todays oil 
crisis might be to return to a national speed limit of 55 miles an 
hour 
later a riegle aide said the senator didnt necessarily support 
a change in the speed limit 
bryan described his bill as a message to detroit and the 
automakers that theyre going to have to look at fuel economy and 
not just muscle cars 
it does not take a crystal ball to realize that if we dont 
start conserving now some future president may have to consider 
sending our young men and woman back to the deserts of the middle 
east he said 
