work on the hibernia oil project 
off newfoundland will start almost immediately now that a formal 
deal has been struck to build the 52 billion 45 billion us 
project federal energy minister jake epp said friday 
this day has been a long time coming but few will have reason 
to doubt that it has been well worth the wait epp told a news 
conference today a major milestone has been reached hibernia 
will bring jobs and economic diversification to newfoundland and 
all of canada 
companies estimate the hibernia field has recoverable oil 
reserves of 525 million to 650 million barrels peak output will be 
about 110000 barrels a day 
the deal involving ottawa the province and a consortium of four 
companies led by mobil oil canada is to be signed when the house of 
commons resumes sept 24 
a bill authorizing ottawas contribution of 27 billion 23 
billion us for canadas largest oil project cannot be passed 
until then 
the rest of the costs will be covered by the consortium and 
newfoundland which will also provide tax breaks during six years 
of construction 
the project will create up to 6000 jobs during contruction and 
about 1100 during production 
mobil kicked off the project friday by announcing the st 
johnsbased company nodeco will construct the gigantic concrete 
underwater base that will hold up the rig platform about 190 miles 
southeast of st johns 
about 3 billion 26 billion worth of construction work will 
go to canadian firms 
epp insisted the project slated to start production in 1996 
and last about 20 years will be profitable although some oil 
analysts doubt that claim 
a senior energy department offical said ottawa and newfoundland 
each stand to make about 37 billion 31 billion us if the 
price of oil averages 30 us in current dollars over the life of 
production 
